history.content:
My suggestion would be to buy the textbook (which is absolutely fantastic) and start reading it, since most of the class follows the book and certainly will do with Papadimitriou, one of the authors. There are problems at the end of each chapter that the staff draw homework problems from.

If you want to do problems, the textbook problems are fine and go from easy to difficult. Some topics early on in the course that people have trouble with: math necessary for asymptotic analysis, complex numbers and FFT.
